**Abstract:** Essay examining the historical formation of the scholastic understanding of faith and reason, focusing on difficulties encountered in applying Aristotelian scientific concepts to biblical texts. Draws extensively on Chenu's analysis while critically questioning the adequacy of Aquinas's synthesis. Explores the resistance of Augustinian wisdom to Aristotelian rationalism and the problematic fit between biblical literary genres and scientific method.
**AI Recommendation:** HIGH - Important companion to OBJECTOR document; presents Monasterio's critical perspective on the scientization of theology and the loss of narrative and symbolic modes of understanding.

